HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1572
By Sparks
A RESOLUTION to honor and commend Wired Human for its
leadership in addressing the youth mental health
crisis and promoting healthy digital engagement
among young people.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly recognize that the mental health
and well-being of Tennessee's youth are essential to the strength and future of this State; and
WHEREAS, emerging data reveals that depression and anxiety related to technology
use have tripled over the past decade, underscoring a growing public health concern; and
WHEREAS, studies indicate that 54 percent of young adults aged eighteen to twenty
report having experienced online sexual harms during childhood, highlighting the urgent need
for awareness, protection, and education; and
WHEREAS, teenagers now spend an average of nine hours per day engaged with digital
media, and adolescents who spend more than three hours daily on social media are twice as
likely to experience anxiety and depression; and
WHEREAS, today's hyper-connected youth are often described as one of the loneliest
generations, with excessive digital engagement and the erosion of deep, meaningful
relationships contributing significantly to this condition; and
WHEREAS, major technology companies generate billions of dollars annually through
youth engagement, including an estimated $11 billion in advertising revenue derived from users
aged 0 to 17 across major social media platforms; and
WHEREAS, in response to these challenges, Wired Human, founded by Jason Frost
and Lisa Frost, has become a leading nonprofit organization dedicated to advocating for a
healthier digital future by equipping, educating, and empowering youth, parents, educators, and
policymakers; and
HJR1572
018538
- 1 -

WHEREAS, the organization provides both awareness and actionable solutions through
its RUMB model—Relationship, Understanding, Mentorship, and Boundaries—helping young
people identify their values and align their daily behaviors accordingly; and
WHEREAS, Wired Human's approach emphasizes empowerment rather than fear,
avoiding shame-based messaging and instead fostering resilience, personal responsibility, and
meaningful human connection; and
WHEREAS, the organization has developed an innovative curriculum for middle school
students, currently under consideration for pilot implementation in six schools in Rutherford
County, which would mark the curriculum's first adoption within a public school system following
successful use in private-school settings; and
WHEREAS, Wired Human further elevates youth voices through artistic expression,
encouraging students to create original works that reflect their lived experiences within the
digital landscape, some of which have been displayed before members of the United States
Senate as part of national advocacy efforts; and
WHEREAS, Wired Human will host a community art exhibition and reception at Trellis &
Vine Art Gallery on Saturday, April 25, 2026, providing an opportunity for youth, parents,
educators, and legislators to engage with these important issues and explore solutions together;
and
WHEREAS, through its youth coalitions and community initiatives, Wired Human
continues to provide critical support and guidance to families, educators, and leaders seeking to
address the challenges of mental health and digital overexposure among today's youth; now,
therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that the members of this General Assembly honor and commend Wired Human
- 2 - 018538

for its outstanding contributions to improving youth mental health and promoting a healthier,
more balanced relationship with technology.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we applaud Wired Human's commitment to
empowering the next generation through education, mentorship, creative expression, and
practical solutions that foster long-term well-being.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we honor Wired Human's initiatives to equip young
people with the necessary tools to thrive in an increasingly digital world.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
- 3 - 018538

